#    Rust ecosystem dev)
#
#  Maintained by Wade Cheng (independent developer).  5 GH stars
#  on compile-typst-site (small but real project, version 2.1.0).
#  compile-typst-site is a static site generator built around
#  TYPST (https://typst.app — modern document-typesetting language
#  designed as a LaTeX alternative with cleaner syntax and faster
#  compilation).  Given a directory of `.typ` Typst source files,
#  compile-typst-site invokes the Typst compiler to render each
#  file to HTML, copies passthrough assets (CSS/JS/images per
#  user-configured globs), runs optional pre-init scripts (e.g.
#  Python build steps), and optional post-processing on the
#  generated HTML (e.g. minification, syntax-highlight injection).
#  Supports --watch mode (rebuild on file changes) and --serve
#  mode (rebuild + serve over HTTP for local development).
#  Configuration via combined CLI flags + TOML config file.
#  Sister tools: hugo (in corpus + STOCK — Go static site
#  generator; the dominant SSG), zola (in corpus + STOCK — Rust
#  SSG by Vincent Prouillet), jekyll (in corpus + STOCK — Ruby
#  SSG; GitHub Pages default), eleventy (in corpus via _11ty —
#  Node.js SSG), astro (in corpus via _astro — modern hybrid
#  islands SSG), gatsby (in corpus via _gatsby — React SSG),
#  next.js (in corpus via _next — React framework with SSG),
#  pelican (in corpus + STOCK — Python SSG), mdbook (in corpus
#  via _mdbook + STOCK Rust — book-format SSG), typst (in corpus
#  via _typst — the underlying document compiler that
#  compile-typst-site wraps).
#
#  CLI library taxonomy update: 21st Rust CLI library — Jay
#  "parasyte" Oster's **onlyargs** (parasyte/onlyargs).  Rust
#  ecosystem now has 21 documented CLI libraries — TYING WITH GO
#  at the top of the cross-language taxonomy ahead of TypeScript-
#  Node (20).  🎉 Rust RE-TIES with Go at 21 — Rust REACHES 21
#  documented CLI libraries.
#
#  onlyargs (parasyte/onlyargs, 18 GH stars) is "Only argument
#  parsing! Nothing more."  Distinguishing philosophy: ABSOLUTE
#  MINIMALISM — onlyargs provides a `Trait OnlyArgs` with `parse
#  (Vec<OsString>) -> Result<Self, CliError>` and ABSOLUTELY
#  NOTHING ELSE.  Helper macros (`onlyargs::impl_help!()` /
#  `onlyargs::impl_version!()`) auto-generate --help and
#  --version strings from struct doc-comments at COMPILE TIME via
#  a separate proc-macro crate `onlyargs_derive`.  Two ways to
#  use:
#    1. MANUAL — implement OnlyArgs trait yourself with a
#       hand-rolled `match arg.to_str()` loop (lowest-level,
#       fully transparent, ZERO proc-macro magic)
#    2. DERIVE — use `#[derive(OnlyArgs)]` from `onlyargs_derive`
#       to auto-generate the parser from struct fields with
#       doc-comments
#  This SPLIT-CRATE design (core trait + optional derive crate)
#  lets users opt into proc-macros only when they want them;
#  manual usage requires ZERO proc-macros and ZERO build-time
#  overhead beyond what stdlib provides.  Used by parasyte/
#  onlyargs (examples), wade-cheng/compile-typst-site (Typst
#  SSG 5 stars), dcdpr/taxcount (airgapped US tax calculation
#  for Bitcoiners 9 stars + 3 helper binaries), and other niche
#  Rust binaries that want minimal-overhead arg parsing without
#  pulling in clap's weight.  Jay Oster is also the author of
#  the `pixels` crate (pixel framebuffer for windowing), `error-
#  iter` (error source iteration helper), and many Rust ecosystem
#  utilities — onlyargs reflects parasyte's general preference
#  for minimal-dependency Rust libraries.
#
